SIMPLE: hum
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hum
<hw>Hum</hw> <pr>(h⟦ucr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hummed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Humming</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Of
imitative origin; cf. G. <ets>hummen</ets>, D. <ets>hommelen</ets>.
⟦root⟧15.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a low, prolonged sound, like
that of a bee in flight; to drone; to murmur; to buzz; <as>as, a top
<ex>hums</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>P. Fletcher.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Still <qex>humming</qex> on, their drowsy course they keep.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a nasal sound, like that of the letter
<xex>m</xex> prolonged, without opening the mouth, or articulating; to
mumble in monotonous undertone; to drone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cloudy messenger turns me his back,⟦br⟧
And <qex>hums</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[Cf. <er>Hum</er>, <ets>interj</ets>.]</ety> <def>To
make an inarticulate sound, like <xex>h'm</xex>, through the nose in the
process of speaking, from embarrassment or a affectation; to
hem.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To express satisfaction by a humming
noise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here the spectators <qex>hummed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Trial of the
Regicides.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Formerly the habit of audiences was to express
gratification by humming and displeasure by hissing.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To have the sensation of a humming noise; <as>as, my
head <ex>hums</ex>, -- a pathological condition</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hum</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hum
<hw>Hum</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sing with shut mouth;
to murmur without articulation; to mumble; <as>as, to <ex>hum</ex> a
tune</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To express satisfaction with by humming.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To flatter by approving; to cajole; to impose on; to
humbug.</def> <mark>[Colloq. & Low]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hum</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hum
<hw>Hum</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A low monotonous noise, as
of bees in flight, of a swiftly revolving top, of a wheel, or the like;
a drone; a buzz.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The shard-borne beetle with his drowsy <qex>hums</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any inarticulate and buzzing sound</def>; as:
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>The confused noise of a crowd or of machinery, etc.,
heard at a distance; <as>as, the <ex>hum</ex> of
industry</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But 'midst the crowd, the <qex>hum</qex>, the shock of men.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A buzz or murmur, as of approbation.</def>
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An imposition or hoax.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[Cf. <er>Hem</er>, <pos>interj.</pos>]</ety> <def>An
inarticulate nasal sound or murmur, like <xex>h'm</xex>, uttered by a
speaker in pause from embarrassment, affectation, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These shrugs, these <qex>hums</qex> and ha's.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[Perh. so called because strongly
intoxicating.]</ety> <def>A kind of strong drink formerly used.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Venous hum</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Venous</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hum</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hum
<hw>Hum</hw>, <pos>interj.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Hem</er>,
<ets>interj</ets>.]</ety> <def>Ahem; hem; an inarticulate sound uttered
in a pause of speech implying doubt and deliberation.</def>
<rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Human</ent>⟦br⟧
